metadata.name: Collapsing System #52
metadata.description:
It started with a simple algorithm for the visualization of our Solar system. Nothing special, just Newton’s laws and gravitation. F = G x m1 x m2 / R^2, a = F / m.

Then it came to thoughts about the end. Planetary systems can live for billion years… until the moment when something breaks their balance. So I decided to model a situation when some stable planetary system encountered a little distortion. And it turns out really fascinating.

Now I want to share it with you - your own planetary system apocalypse. 

Press 1 to save png with 2400px resolution.
Press 2 to save png with 4800px resolution.
Press 3 to save png with 9600px resolution.

It makes take some time to render, please be patient.

metadata.name: SCRIBBLERS #3
metadata.description:
Generative animated drawing inspired by mindless doodling and low-res CAD graphics. Custom physics engine made with vanilla javascript. Colors quantized with GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

Use mouse/touch to drag scribbles around and untangle them.
Press ’s’ key to save PNG (live mode only).
Screen size responsive.

metadata.description:
An ode to my print background. 
My love of process flaws, from offsetting to uneven ink coverage.

metadata.name: Badgirs City #136
metadata.description:
"I used to live in a small city placed at the center of Iran's plateau with the warmest summer days in the country part; spending most of my childhood with my sweet grandma at her old house. She was always keeping her eyes on me not to get heat stroke at noon playing in the yard when the sun was at its peak glowing furiously. Sundays at noon were my favorite, I used to call them “Ice cream” noons sitting beside the nicest person you could imagine and enjoying a delightful ice cream. You won't know how lovely it was to have an ice cream relaxing under the most enjoyable cold breeze of the tallest windcatcher in the city at her house. "



The Badgirs city is the first collaboration between Fleep and IceRain on Fxhash. The concept was established first with the design of a school with a feeling of safe and nostalgia reminding us of the good memories of our childhood as the grandma’s house and the windcatcher for Fleep.
A windcatcher (Badgir) is an Iranian traditional architectural element in the form of a small tower built on the roof of houses in warm locations to create passive cooling. The collection of Badgirs city is a modern recreational development of those traditional windcatchers designed by Fleep and icerain and exquisitely translated into code by Icerain.

Controls:
[1] Set the resolution to Medium Resolution
[2] Set the resolution to High Resolution

metadata.name: Resilience  #21
metadata.description:
Resilience is a collection of endless architectures.
In a resilient generative system composed of multiple compatible parts, real-time information exchange enables open reconfigurations and continuous discrete adjustments. Sometimes vague and fuzzy, sometimes real and tangible, they reveal different readings of architectural complexity and scale: from city plans to floor plans and details to sections and elevations.

Resilience comes in a variety of polychrome palettes, ascii glyphs, and styles. 
To enjoy it in full-screen mode, press the left mouse button in live mode, for a monochrome look press 'b'. Made with P5js.

Resilience Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2022

metadata.name: Urban Flora #107
metadata.description:
Urban Flora is a generative artwork exploring interplay of natural and artificial forms created by Marcin Ignac / @marcinignac

http://marcinignac.com/projects/urban-flora/

The project was inspired by the 3/4/5G network infrastructure more and more present in the parks and greenery of our cities. Final Urban Flora transformed into a study of abandoned structures of a long forgotten civilisation.

The whole image is generative and/or procedural. Leaves are parametric, twigs and trees use the space colonisation algorithm, and the geometry is based on platonic solids transformed though series of operations.

Features determined at the time of minting:
- one of the platonic solids or a prism
- one of 15 geometry transformations
- a color theme
- leaves or detailed twigs
- leaf's spread and the amount of ridges

'g' / 'tree finger tap' - resolution and export
'drag' - rotate
'scroll' - zoom (on desktop)

Please note the project needs a decent GPU.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

--
With dedication to my wife.

metadata.name: Organicon, variation I #366
metadata.description:
Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
A unique generator creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation I is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. Warning: the preview thumbnail is a pale shadow of live view.

Interface: a first mouse click clears the screen, creates an new iteration and enables active mode. In active mode each iteration remains on screen for a limited amount of time before being replaced by the next. A second mouse click disables active mode. In active mode a small dot is displayed in the lower right corner. '+' and '-' zoom in and out.

metadata.name: Tranquility #64
metadata.description:
There was an original meaning to this piece, but it washed away over time, nevertheless Tranquility is a representation of the challenges of connecting to others and the resilience required to navigate the complexity of human relationships. Tranquility features sharp and dynamic lines that result in intricate and often chaotic patterns (conveying the intensity and complexity of the human experience).

Generative artwork - www.petitsapin.com
Press "s" in live view to download high-res version.
